You need two things: a **navigation guard** in `AppShell` and a **custom back button** on the page.

### 1. Guard navigation in `AppShell.xaml.cs`

Use `OnNavigating` with `GetDeferral()` to intercept back navigation:

```csharp
protected override async void OnNavigating(ShellNavigatingEventArgs args)
{
    base.OnNavigating(args);

    if (args.Source == ShellNavigationSource.Pop
        && Shell.Current.CurrentPage is EditProductPage page
        && page.HasUnsavedChanges)
    {
        var deferral = args.GetDeferral();

        bool discard = await Shell.Current.CurrentPage.DisplayAlert(
            "Unsaved Changes",
            "You have unsaved changes. Discard them?",
            "Discard", "Stay");

        if (!discard)
            args.Cancel();

        deferral.Complete();
    }
}
```

> **Key:** You must call `GetDeferral()` *before* the `await` and `deferral.Complete()` *after* — otherwise the navigation completes before your async dialog returns.

### 2. Custom "Cancel" back button on `EditProductPage.xaml`

```xml
<ContentPage xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui"
             xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml"
             x:Class="MyApp.Views.EditProductPage"
             Title="Edit Product">

    <Shell.BackButtonBehavior>
        <BackButtonBehavior TextOverride="Cancel"
                            Command="{Binding BackCommand}" />
    </Shell.BackButtonBehavior>

    <!-- page content -->
</ContentPage>
```

### 3. Expose `HasUnsavedChanges` and the back command

```csharp
// EditProductPage.xaml.cs
public partial class EditProductPage : ContentPage
{
    public bool HasUnsavedChanges { get; set; }
}
```

```csharp
// In your ViewModel
[RelayCommand]
async Task Back()
{
    await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("..");
}
```

When the user taps "Cancel", the `BackCommand` calls `GoToAsync("..")`, which triggers the `OnNavigating` guard — so the confirmation dialog appears whether they use the custom button or the system back gesture.
